ling\n| TranslitTitle       = Riku Hakugen, Akaki Hoshi Otsu Goj\u014dhen ni Mau\n| NativeTitle         = \u9678\u4f2f\u8a00\u3001\u7d05\u304d\u661f\u843d\u3064\u4e94\u4e08\u539f\u306b\u821e\u3046\n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja \n| OriginalAirDate     = {{Start date|2007|9|27}}\n}}\n|}\n\n==Theme songs==\n'''Opening:'''\n# \"Nostalgia\" by [[Camino (band)|Camino]]\n\n'''Ending:'''\n# \"[[Kuon (song)|Kuon]]\" by [[Miyano Mamoru]]\n\n'''Insert Songs:'''\n# \"Koubou\" by Miyano Mamoru (episode 25)\n\n==Reception==\n\n{{empty section|date=March 2015}}\n\n==References==\n* http://yueying.net/dw/?page=names.japanese Names in Romance of the Three Kingdoms in their Chinese and Japanese versions\n\n==External links==\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20070829030103/http://www.koutetsu-sangokushi.jp/file/jsp/\n* {{ann|anime|7513}}\n\n{{Romance of the Three Kingdoms}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kotetsu Sangokushi}}\n[[Category:Action anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Fantasy anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Historical anime and manga]]\n[[Category:2006 manga]]\n[[Category:Supernatural anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Works based on Romance of the Three Kingdoms]]\n[[Category:Sh\u014dnen-ai anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Anime series]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K%C5%8Dtetsu_Sangokushi"}
{"title_page": "The World's Greatest First Love", "text_new": "{{Infobox animanga/Header\n| name            = The World's Greatest First Love\n| image           = [[File:Sekai-ichi Hatsukoi.jpg|230px]]\n| caption         = Cover of ''Sekai-ichi Hatsukoi'' volume 1\n| ja_kanji        = \u4e16\u754c\u4e00\u521d\u604b\n| ja_romaji       = Sekai Ichi Hatsukoi\n| genre           = [[Romance novel|Romance]], [[Comedy]], [[Yaoi]], [[Slice of life]]\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Print\n| type            = manga\n| title           = The World's Greatest First Love: The Case of Ritsu Oneodera\n| author          = [[Shungiku Nakamura]]\n| publisher       = [[Kadokawa Shoten]]\n| publisher_en    = {{English manga publisher|NA= [[Viz Media|SuBLime]]}}\n| demographic     = ''[[Josei manga|Josei]]''\n| imprint         = \n| magazine        = Emerald\n| first           = October 13, 2006\n| volumes         = 13\n| volume_list     = #Manga\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Print\n| type            = light novel\n| title           = Sekai-ichi Hatsukoi: Yoshino Chiaki no Baai\n| author          = [[Shungiku Nakamura]]\n| publisher       = [[Kadokawa Shoten]]\n| demographic     = Josei\n| imprint           = \n| magazine        = \n| first           = November 1, 2007\n| last            = \n| volumes         = 4\n| volume_list     = \n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type            = ova\n| title           = Sekai-ichi Hatsukoi: No love's like to the first.\n| director        = [[Chiaki Kon]]\n| producer        =\n| writer          = [[Rika Nakase]]\n| music           = [[Hijiri Anze]]\n| studio          = [[Studio Deen]]\n| licensee        = {{English anime licensee\n |NA=[[Funimation]]\n}}\n| released        = March 22, 2011\n| runtime         = 30 minutes\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type            = tv series\n| director        = [[Chiaki Kon]]\n| producer        =\n| writer          = Rika Nakase\n| music           = Hijiri Anze\n| studio          = Studio Deen\n| licensee        = {{English anime licensee\n |NA=[[Funimation]]\n}}\n| network         = [[TV Saitama]]\n| first           = April 9, 2011\n| last            = June 25, 2011\n| episodes        = 12\n| episode_list    = #Season 1\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type            = ova\n| title           = Sekai-ichi Hatsukoi: Hatori Yoshiyuki no Baai\n| director        = Chiaki Kon\n| producer        =\n| writer          = Rika Nakase\n| music           = Hijiri Anze\n| studio          = Studio Deen\n| licensee        = {{English anime licensee\n |NA=[[Funimation]]\n}}\n| released        = September 27, 2011\n| runtime         = 30 minutes\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type            = tv series\n| title           = Sekai-ichi Hatsukoi 2\n| director        = Chiaki Kon\n| producer        =\n| writer          = Rika Nakase\n| music           = Hijiri Anze\n| studio          = Studio Deen\n| licensee        = {{English anime licensee\n |NA=[[Funimation]]\n}}\n| network         = TV Saitama\n| first           = October 7, 2011\n| last            = December 23, 2011\n| episodes        = 12\n| episode_list    = #Season 2\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Print\n| type            = light novel\n| title           = Sekai-ichi Hatsukoi: Yokozawa Takafumi no Baai\n| author          = [[Shungiku Nakamura]]\n| publisher       = [[Kadokawa Shoten]]\n| demographic     = Josei\n| imprint           = \n| first           = November 1, 2011\n| last            = \n| volumes         = 6\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type            = film\n| title           = Sekai-ichi Hatsukoi: Yokozawa Takafumi no Baai\n| director        = Chiaki Kon \n| studio          = Studio Deen\n| released        = {{Start date|2014|03|15}}\n| runtime         = 50 minutes\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type            = film\n| title           = Sekai-ichi Hatsukoi: Propose-hen\n| director        = Tomoya Takahashi \n| studio          = Studio Deen\n| released        = {{Start date|2020|02|21}}\n| runtime         = \n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Footer}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''''The World's Greatest First Love: The Case of Ritsu Onodera'''''|\u4e16\u754c\u4e00\u521d\u604b \u301c\u5c0f\u91ce\u5bfa\u5f8b\u306e\u5834\u5408\u301c|Sekai-Ichi Hatsukoi: Onodera Ritsu no Baai|also alternatively known as '''''Sekai Ichi Hatsukoi: The World's Greatest First Love''''' in the English anime}} is a Japanese [[yaoi]] [[manga]] series written and illustrated by [[Shungiku Nakamura]]. In 2011, the manga was adapted into an anime television series. Produced by [[Studio Deen]] under the direction of [[Chiaki Kon]], the [[anime]] series began its broadcast run on April 9, 2011.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2010-11-29/sekai-ichi-hatsukoi-tv-anime-dated-for-april-2011 | title = ''Sekai-ichi Hatsukoi'' TV Anime Dated for April 2011 | publisher = Anime News Network | date = November 29, 2010 | accessdate = February 22, 2011}}</ref> An [[original animation DVD]] was bundled with the fifth and sixth volumes of the manga series, released in March and September 2011.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2010-07-01/sekai-ichi-hatsukoi-boys-love-manga-to-bundle-anime-dvd | title = ''Sekai-ichi'' Hatsukoi Boys-Love Manga to Bundle Anime DVD | publisher = Anime News Network | date = July 1, 2010 | accessdate = February 22, 2011}}</ref> A film adaptation was released on March 15, 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-12-26/sekai-ichi-hatsukoi-film-slated-for-march-15|title= Sekai-ichi Hatsukoi Film Slated for March 15|date= 2013-12-26|accessdate= 2013-12-29|work= [[Anime News Network]]}}</ref>\n\nOn December 13, 2016, [[Funimation]] announced they had licensed the series, including the OVA. It was released on home-video March 7, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-12-13/funimation-to-release-sekai-ichi-hatsukoi-the-world-greatest-first-love-anime-on-home-video/.109872|title=Funimation to Release ''Sekai Ichi Hatsukoi \u2013 The World's Greatest First Love'' Anime on Home Video\n|accessdate= 2016-12-13|work= [[Anime News Network]]}}</ref>\n\nA new anime adaptation focused on the Proposal Arc has been announced to celebrate the fifth anniversary of the new ''Emerald'' magazine.  It will premiere in February 21, 2020.\n\n''Sekai-ichi Hatsukoi'' is an spin-off of ''[[Junjo Romantica]]'', another series by the same author.\n\n== Plot ==\nRitsu Onodera, a literary editor, resigns from his father's publishing company, due to his coworkers' jealousy toward his success, claiming that he is simply riding his father's coattails. He applies for a position at Marukawa Publishing in order to move away from his father's shadow, but instead of his preferred department of literature, he is placed in the infamous [[sh\u014djo manga]] department, Emerald. He initially considers resigning, especially because he finds his new boss, Masamune Takano, intolerable and unnerving from the very beginning; however, Takano inadvertently convinces Onodera to stick with the job by calling him \"useless,\" his pride forcing him to stay in order to prove his worth. Later, Onodera learns that Takano's old family name was Saga, and that he was an older schoolmate from high school that Onodera fell in love with and confessed to. It turns out Takano still has feelings for Onodera, and he tells him he will make him fall in love with him again. The series shows how Takano slowly achieves this goal, and the obstacles the two face.\n\nThere are also two other couples in this show; their stories are shown in later episodes. The characters follow Onodera's fellow editors: Hatori and his longtime friend (and manga artist he's in charge of) Yoshino, as well as Kisa and the attractive bookstore employee he has his eye on, Yukina.\n\nAn extra novel follows salesman and longtime friend of Takano's, Yokozawa, as he's swept off his feet following a harsh breakup by attractive widower and single father Kirishima.\n\n== Characters ==\n\n;{{nihongo|Ritsu Onodera|\u5c0f\u91ce\u5bfa \u5f8b|Onodera Ritsu}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Takashi Kond\u014d]]}}\n:Ritsu Onodera is a 25-year-old jaded literary editor. He is the only son of the head of Onodera Publications, previously working at his father's company in the literature department. Hearing his fellow co-workers accusing him of only getting ahead due to his father's influence, he decides to show that he can be successful on his own by going to work at Marukawa Publishing. After being hurt by his first love in high school when he was 15, Onodera vowed to never fall in love again. His resolve is tested, however, when he is reunited with the boy he once loved, Masamune Takano. With Takano now very much a man and his new boss, things become very complicated for Onodera as he must juggle his career and his feelings for his first love.\n:Before transferring to Marukawa Publishing, Onodera was an editor in charge Ryouichi Sumi, father of Misaki's friend Keiichi Sumi (also from ''Junjou Romantica'').\n\n;{{nihongo|Masamune Takano|\u9ad8\u91ce \u653f\u5b97|Takano Masamune}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Katsuyuki Konishi]]}}\n:The 27-year-old Masamune Takano, formerly known as Masamune Saga before his parents' divorce and his mother's remarriage, is the [[editor-in-chief]] of the ''Emerald'' department at Marukawa Publishing, where he is sometimes referred to as \"the Capable.\" He and Onodera were once in a brief relationship in high school, but split up over a misunderstanding. It is later revealed that, during college, Takano went through a breakdown from his breakup with Onodera, family problems, and other personal issues, which in turn left him with unresolved feelings for Onodera. When both he and Onodera realize who each other are, he promises Onodera that he will make him fall in love with him again, much to Onodera's contempt.\n:In ''Sekai-ichi Hatsukoi: Takano Masamune no Baai'' (lit. \"Masamune Takano's Case\"), the reader sees Takano's perspective on his and Onodera's first meeting and romantic development.\n\n;{{nihongo|An Kohinata|\u5c0f\u65e5\u5411 \u674f|Kohinata An}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Yukari Tamura]]}}\n:An Kohinata is Onodera's childhood friend and his fianc\u00e9e, due to an agreement their parents made when the two were kids; however, Onodera does not view her as his fianc\u00e9e. Sweet, polite and sensitive, An has deep feelings for him, despite being rejected by Onodera (whom she calls \"Ricchan\") when she confessed her love.\n\n;{{nihongo|Arata Haitani|\u7070\u8c37 \u65b0|Haitani Arata}}\n:Haitani is Takano's former co-worker at his previous job. He wishes to take revenge on Takano's for \"stealing\" his ex-lover. He seems to develop feelings for Ritsu, though it is unknown where it's genuine or not. He is later revealed to be bisexual.\n\n;{{nihongo|Chiaki Yoshino|\u5409\u91ce \u5343\u79cb|Yoshino Chiaki}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Shinnosuke Tachibana]]}}\n:Chiaki Yoshino is a 28-year-old sh\u014djo manga artist known under the [[pseudonym]] Chiharu Yoshikawa (a female name). His editor in-charge is Hatori Yoshiyuki, who is also his childhood friend. His two best friends are Hatori and Yuu Yanase, but the lines between friendship and love begin to blur after a number of confusing incidents. Yoshino begins to question his feelings for Hatori after witnessing him and Yanase together in what he thinks is a kiss; then Hatori kisses him one night and confesses his feelings. Yoshino begins to realize he has to confront his true feelings or risk losing them both.\n\n;{{nihongo|Yoshiyuki Hatori|\u7fbd\u9ce5 \u82b3\u96ea|Yoshiyuki Hatori}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Yuichi Nakamura (voice actor)|Yuichi Nakamura]]}}\n:Hatori, also known as Tori, is 28 years old and an editor in Marukawa's ''Emerald'' department. Although in the beginning he is seen as serious and reserved, it is later revealed that he has secretly harbored deep feelings for his childhood friend, Yoshino. After confessing his love, Hatori pulls away fearing that Yoshino doesn't feel the same, who he believes loves his rival, Yanase, instead. However, unbeknownst to Hatori, Yoshino does somewhat return those same feelings.<ref>[http://www.kadokawa.co.jp/lnovel/bk_detail.php?pcd=200708000161 Yoshino Chiaki no Baai volume 1]</ref>\n\n;{{nihongo|Yuu Yanase|\u67f3\u702c \u512a|Yanase Y\u016b}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Hiroshi Kamiya]]}}\n:Chief assistant for manga artist Chiaki Yoshino, Yuu Yanase came to know both Hatori and Yoshino when they were in junior high school. An immediate tension is visible between Hatori and Yuu, though it isn't until later that it is discovered that both are vying for the love of Yoshino.\n\n;{{nihongo|Shouta Kisa|\u6728\u4f50 \u7fd4\u592a|Kisa Sh\u014dta}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Nobuhiko Okamoto]]}}\n:Kisa is a fellow editor in the ''Emerald'' department and 30 years old, though he is usually mistaken for being much younger due to his looks. He considers himself gay but has never been in a serious relationship; in fact, he doesn't think himself capable of being in one because of his tendency to fall for a guy's good looks without knowing their personality. Because of this, he immediately questions his feelings for Kou and doesn't hold out much hope for a relationship with him. His mentality can be described by his line, \"Love at first sight works well enough in manga, but this is reality.\"\n\n;{{nihongo|Kou Yukina|\u96ea\u540d \u7687|Yukina K\u014d}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Tomoaki Maeno]]}}\n:Kou Yukina is a 21-year-old clerk in charge of the sh\u014djo manga section at the popular bookstore, Marimo Books. He's been aware of Kisa coming in to watch him, though he initially believed Kisa was just a shy high school student. When he discovers that Kisa is the editor behind all of his favorite works, however, he begins to develop romantic feelings for him, despite considering himself straight prior to their meeting. Throughout their relationship, Kou shows that he is more than willing to fight for Kisa, whom he tries to make understand that what they feel for each other is real and whom he believes to have the capability to fall in love.\n\n;{{nihongo|Takafumi Yokozawa|\u6a2a\u6fa4\u9686\u53f2|Yokozawa Takafumi}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Kenyu Horiuchi]]}}\n:Yokozawa works in the sales department at Marukawa. He is a close friend of Takano's, with whom he had a physical relationship when they were both in college. It is common knowledge in the publishing world that Yokozawa helped Takano get into publishing and his position at Marukawa. He is seriously jealous of and resents Onodera, whom he blames for \"screwing up\" Takano ten years ago. He often warns Onodera away from Takano, even going as far as proclaiming Takano is his.\n:He has his own side story entitled ''Takafumi Yokozawa No Baai'' about his new love interest, Kirishima Zen, as he handles his rejection by Takano.\n\n;{{nihongo|Zen Kirishima|\u6850\u5d8b\u7985|Kirishima Zen}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[T\u014dru Furuya]]}}\n:Zen Kirishima was first introduced in ''[[Junjou Romantica]]'' as the editor-in-chief of ''Japun'', the sh\u014dnen manga magazine; here, he is now the new love interest for Yokozawa. He is raising his daughter, Hiyori, on his own due to his wife's passing a few years ago. After blackmailing Yokozawa, the two begin dating upon realizing their feelings for one another. He has a habit of teasing Yokozawa, calling him the \"mother\" of his daughter Hiyori.\n\n;{{nihongo|Hiyori Kirishima|\u6850\u5d8b\u65e5\u548c|Kirishima Hiyori}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Yui Horie]]}}\n:Hiyori is the 10-year-old daughter and only child of Zen Kirishima and his wife, the latter of whom died some time ago. She bonds quickly with Yokozawa, to whom she refers as \"Onii-san\" (big brother/older male figure). She's responsible for cooking her father's meals and is very fond of kittens and green tea sweets.\n\n;{{nihongo|Kanade Mino|\u7f8e\u6fc3\u594f|Mino Kanade}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Hikaru Midorikawa]]}}\n:Kanade Mino is a fellow editor in the ''Emerald'' department at Marukawa, who is constantly smiling through all the stress and exhaustion. It has been hinted that he has a dark side, with Takano stating, \"Make sure you don't make Mino upset.\"\n\n;{{nihongo|Ry\u016bichir\u014d Isaka|\u4e95\u5742 \u9f8d\u4e00\u90ce|Isaka Ry\u016bichir\u014d}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Toshiyuki Morikawa]]}}\n:Isaka is the president of Marukawa Publishing and he is acquainted with Onodera's parents. He also appears as a character in ''[[Junjou Romantica]]''. In \"Junjou Mistake,\" the reader learns he has been in a relationship with his secretary/childhood playmate Asahina for the past ten years after both acknowledged their mutual feelings. He once aspired to be a novelist, but realized his real talents lay in finding future best-sellers. Like Onodera, others once implied that Isaka's success only came from his family's influence (when in reality it was his talent in nurturing authors to greatness), so he feels a kinship with Onodera, which annoys Onodera who wants to get away from that image.\n\n;{{nihongo|Kaoru Asahina|\u671d\u6bd4\u5948 \u85ab|Asahina Kaoru}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Ry\u014dtar\u014d Okiayu]]}}\n:Asahina is Ry\u016bichiro's assistant, who came to work for the Isaka family when they helped the Asahina family out of a bad situation. Originally intended to be Isaka's playmate, he ended up becoming something more of a caretaker and developed feelings for Isaka at a young age.\n\n;{{nihongo|Saiki|\u5f69\u7d00}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Mai Nakahara]]}}\n:Ritsu's close friend and former co-worker from Onedera Publication, Ritsu's family's company.\n\n;{{nihongo|Erika Ichinose|\u4e00\u4e4b \u702c\u7d75\u68a8\u4f73|Ichinose Erika}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Sayaka Ohara]]}}\n:A famous [[mangaka]] working for Emerald at Marukawa Publishing. Because her work is extremely popular, she is very wealthy and lives a luxurious lifestyle.\n\n== Media ==\n\n=== Manga ===\n\nWritten and illustrated by [[Shungiku Nakamura]], ''Sekai-ichi Hatsukoi'' began serialization in the November 2006 issue of ''The Ruby'' magazine, which went on sale October 13, 2006. It moved to ''Asuka Ciel'' magazine in July 2009 where it continued through May 2014. Publisher Kadokawa announced in May 2014 that it would launch a real-life version of the ''Emerald'' manga magazine from Shungiku Nakamura's ''Sekai-ichi Hatsukoi'' manga. As of August 2014, ''Sekai-ichi Hatsukoi'' and Nakamura's other manga ''[[Junjou Romantica]]'' have switched publications to ''Emerald'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kadokawa.co.jp/company/release/detail.html?id=2014200689 |script-title=ja:\u5927\u30d2\u30c3\u30c8\u30b3\u30f3\u30c6\u30f3\u30c4\u300e\u4e16\u754c\u4e00\u521d\u604b\u300f\u306b\u767b\u5834\u3059\u308b\u3042\u306e\u96d1\u8a8c\u304c\u3001\u307e\u3055\u304b\u306e\u30ea\u30a2\u30eb\u520a\u884c\uff01\uff1f\u3000\u65b0\u5897\u520a\u8a8c\u300e\u30a8\u30e1\u30e9\u30eb\u30c9\u300f\u8a95\u751f\uff01|publisher=[[Kadokawa Shoten]] |language=Japanese|accessdate=2014-09-08 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-05-27/kadokawa-launches-sekai-ichi-hatsukoi-manga-magazine-emerald-in-real-life/.74918 |title=Kadokawa Launches Sekai-ichi Hatsukoi's Manga Magazine Emerald in Real Life |publisher=[[Anime News Network]] |accessdate=2014-09-08 }}</ref> The individual chapters have been released as eleven tank\u014dbon volumes by [[Kadokawa Shoten]]'s ''Asuka Comic CL-DX'' branch. The first volume was published on July 1, 2008, and the ninth on August 29, 2014.\n\nThe first eight volumes of ''Sekai-ichi Hatsukoi'' have been licensed for an English release in February 2015 by SuBlime, a subsidiary of North American manga publisher Viz Media. The English title will be ''The World's Greatest First Love: The Case of Ritsu Onodera'', and volume one will print in February 2015. Subsequent releases will be every other month thereafter.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sublimemanga.com/news/261 |title=NEW TITLE ANNOUNCEMENT! |publisher=SuBlime |accessdate=2014-09-08 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-06-30/viz-media-sublime-imprint-adds-shungiku-nakamura-sekai-ichi-hatsukoi/.76165 |title=Viz Media's SuBLime Imprint Adds Shungiku Nakamura's Sekai-ichi Hatsukoi |publisher=[[Anime News Network]] |accessdate=2014-09-08 }}</ref> The series was originally licensed for English-language release in North America by [[Tokyopop]]'s [[Blu Manga]], with volume 1 due for release on 12 July 2011 but went unused due to the 31 May 2011 closure of [[Tokyopop]]'s publishing efforts.<ref name=\"Tokyopop Shutting Down\">{{cite web |url=http://www.comicsbeat.com/2011/04/15/end-of-an-era-tokyopop-shutting-down/ |title=End of an era: Tokyopop shutting down US publishing division |publisher=[[Comics Beat]]|accessdate=2011-07-01 }}</ref>\n\n{{Graphic novel list/header}}\n{{Graphic novel list\n | VolumeNumber = 1\n | OriginalRelDate = July 1, 2008<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kadokawa.co.jp/comic/bk_detail.php?pcd=200801000634 |script-title=ja:\u5c0f\u91ce\u5bfa\u5f8b\u306e\u5834\u5408|publisher=[[Kadokawa Shoten]] |language=Japanese |accessdate=2011-05-22 }}</ref>\n | OriginalISBN = 978-4-04-854190-9\n | LicensedRelDate = February 10, 2015\n | LicensedISBN = 978-1421579160\n | ChapterList = *The Case of Onodera Ritsu No. 1\n*The Case of Onodera Ritsu No. 2\n*The Case of Onodera Ritsu No. 2.5\n | Summary = \n}}\n{{Graphic novel list\n | VolumeNumber = 2\n | OriginalRelDate = August 1, 2009<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kadokawa.co.jp/comic/bk_detail.php?pcd=200904000063 |script-title=ja:\u5c0f\u91ce\u5bfa\u5f8b\u306e\u5834\u54082|publisher=[[Kadokawa Shoten]] |language=Japanese |accessdate=2011-05-22 }}</ref>\n | OriginalISBN = 978-4-04-854351-4\n | LicensedRelDate = July 14, 2015\n | LicensedISBN = 978-1421579177\n | ChapterList = *The Case of Onodera Ritsu No. 3\n* The Case of Onodera Ritsu No. 4\n* The Case of Onodera Ritsu No. 4.5\n | Summary = \n}}\n{{Graphic novel list\n | VolumeNumber = 3\n | OriginalRelDate = October 1, 2